  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Developing Core Components**\n\nI\'ve just finalized the basic component architecture. I\'ve got the TypeScript models sorted in `/src/types.ts`. I\'ve also implemented distance and bearing calculations with a dynamic mock shop generator in `/src/data/mockShops.ts`, which I\'m quite pleased with. Additionally, I\'ve created the responsive circular compass in `/src/components/Compass.tsx` and the canvas sonar radar in `/src/components/Radar.tsx`.\n\n\n**Orchestrating App State**\n\nI\'m now focusing on `/src/App.tsx`. I\'ve outlined the necessary states: `mode`, `userLocation`, `userHeading`, `shops`, and `selectedShop`. I plan to integrate a toggle switch for the `mode`, with a default geolocation and potential geolocation grab on mount. I\'ll dynamically generate the `shops` list, based on the `userLocation` and automatically select the closest shop based on the new mode upon mode change.\n\n\n**Implementing Mode Switches**\n\nI\'ve got the state flow mostly defined now. The `App.tsx` file handles the core logic. Mode changes will trigger updates to the `selectedShop`, locking onto the nearest milk tea shop or bar, dynamically. The app logic now completely addresses the question of \"automatically pointing out the closest milk tea shop/bar\" and the mode-based switching. Additionally, I\'ve got the `activeTab` and `sensorStatus` state enumerated. I\'ve now finished the geolocation handler, and I\'ve started the implementation of the compass orientation handler.\n\n\n**Handling Device Orientation**\n\nI\'ve just added the `handleOrientation` function to manage device heading, using both `webkitCompassHeading` for iOS and alpha for Android. I\'ve also implemented `requestDeviceOrientation` to request permission on supported devices, crucial for accurate compass readings. I am now working on integrating this with the existing state management, particularly `userHeading`.\n\n\n**Refining Sensor Activation**\n\nI\'ve just refined the sensor activation logic. I\'m now handling device orientation permissions. I\'m checking the permission state and adding an event listener if the permission is granted. A catch block handles errors, while the checkEvent function on standard Android or desktops determines if the sensors are actually active. I\'ve set the sensor status accordingly, whether it is available or unavailable.\n\n\n**Adding Simulation Controls**\n\nI\'m now integrating \"Simulation Mode\" controls below the main view. There will be a city preset teleport that instantly re-centers the map and re-generates shops based on city landmarks. Additionally, I\'m implementing a \"Walk Simulator Joystick\" with a \"Take 50m step forward\" button. This button will shift the user\'s location based on the current heading using the `destinationPoint` function. This feature adds a new depth of user interaction!\n\n\n**Validating Integration**\n\nNow I\'m verifying the complete integration. Rotating the compass, simulating a step forward, and observing the map update, distance decrease, and radar dots converge is incredibly satisfying! I\'m also reviewing the imports in `/src/App.tsx` to ensure everything is connected and there are no linting errors.\n\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now write the full implementation of `/src/App.tsx`. It coordinates the primary application state:\n1. **Compass Mode Toggle (\'milktea\' vs \'bar\')**: Features a dynamic design with smooth custom transitions. When toggling, it automatically locks onto the closest shop of the new mode and re-calculates target arrows.\n2. **Tab Controller**: Switches between the circular **Compass** view, the scanning **Sonar Radar** view, and the interactive **Leaflet Map** view.\n3. **Dynamic Shop Seeder**: Updates all shop distances and bearings whenever the user\'s location coordinates change.\n4. **Walk Simulator**: Enables desktop users to \"take steps\" in their current facing direction, letting them watch the compass distance tick down and the radar blips drift closer in real-time.\n5. **City Teleporter**: Provides one-click presets for cities like Beijing Sanlitun and Chengdu Chunxi Road.\n6. **Mobile Sensor Integration**: Accesses real geolocation (GPS) and physical gyroscope compass events where available. Let\'s create it."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 8
      nanos: 869972943
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
