  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Gyroscope Access**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the user\'s issue with the unavailable gyroscope on a real phone. I\'m digging into why this is happening and possible solutions. The initial observation points towards a crucial security/privacy constraint on mobile browsers, primarily iOS Safari and newer Android Chrome versions: access is limited in insecure contexts. Specifically, the HTTPS requirement seems to be a major factor.\n\n\n**Investigating iFrame Restrictions**\n\nI\'ve hit a roadblock with the gyroscope \342\200\223 specifically, the iFrame embedding of the app seems to be a key issue. It seems our iFrame\'s default lack of `accelerometer` and `gyroscope` permissions might be the culprit. The lack of `allow=\"accelerometer; gyroscope; magnetometer\"` attribute on the iFrame is definitely something I need to check. I\'ll need to check the code that currently handles requesting device orientation. I\'m focusing on the `src/App.tsx` file for now, specifically the `requestDeviceOrientation` trigger, and also the binding in `src/components/Compass.tsx`.\n\n\n**Examining Code Implementation**\n\nI\'m now diving deep into the code, especially focusing on the `onClick={requestDeviceOrientation}` trigger and its associated element ID, `auth-gyro`. Specifically, I\'m analyzing the `src/App.tsx` file and pinpointing the gyroscope permission request implementation for iOS, checking its logic. I\'m also scrutinizing the fallback for Android and other standards within the same file to grasp the full device orientation handling strategy, paying attention to the `checkEvent` function.\n\n\n**Refining Event Handling**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the event handling and permission strategies. Specifically, I\'m examining the `checkEvent` function\'s logic within the `deviceorientation` listener, looking for optimization. I\'m focusing on the condition checks, particularly the `e.alpha !== null` and `webkitCompassHeading` aspects to enhance the accuracy of gyroscope status updates. The goal is to refine the `setSensorStatus` to accurately reflect gyroscope availability, addressing inconsistencies.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 183773296
    }
